#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:5
msgid "Architecture overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:7
msgid ""
"This document describes the architecture of Scrapy and how its components "
"interact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:11
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:13
msgid ""
"The following diagram shows an overview of the Scrapy architecture with its "
"components and an outline of the data flow that takes place inside the "
"system (shown by the green arrows). A brief description of the components is "
"included below with links for more detailed information about them. The data "
"flow is also described below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:-1
msgid "Scrapy architecture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:25
msgid "Components"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:28
msgid "Scrapy Engine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:30
msgid ""
"The engine is responsible for controlling the data flow between all "
"components of the system, and triggering events when certain actions occur. "
"See the Data Flow section below for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:35
msgid "Scheduler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:37
msgid ""
"The Scheduler receives requests from the engine and enqueues them for "
"feeding them later (also to the engine) when the engine requests them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:41
msgid "Downloader"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:43
msgid ""
"The Downloader is responsible for fetching web pages and feeding them to the "
"engine which, in turn, feeds them to the spiders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:47
msgid "Spiders"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:49
msgid ""
"Spiders are custom classes written by Scrapy users to parse responses and "
"extract items (aka scraped items) from them or additional URLs (requests) to "
"follow. Each spider is able to handle a specific domain (or group of "
"domains). For more information see :ref:`topics-spiders`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:55
msgid "Item Pipeline"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:57
msgid ""
"The Item Pipeline is responsible for processing the items once they have "
"been extracted (or scraped) by the spiders. Typical tasks include cleansing, "
"validation and persistence (like storing the item in a database). For more "
"information see :ref:`topics-item-pipeline`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:63
msgid "Downloader middlewares"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:65
msgid ""
"Downloader middlewares are specific hooks that sit between the Engine and "
"the Downloader and process requests when they pass from the Engine to the "
"Downloader, and responses that pass from Downloader to the Engine. They "
"provide a convenient mechanism for extending Scrapy functionality by "
"plugging custom code. For more information see :ref:`topics-downloader-"
"middleware`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:72
msgid "Spider middlewares"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:74
msgid ""
"Spider middlewares are specific hooks that sit between the Engine and the "
"Spiders and are able to process spider input (responses) and output (items "
"and requests). They provide a convenient mechanism for extending Scrapy "
"functionality by plugging custom code. For more information see :ref:`topics-"
"spider-middleware`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:81
msgid "Data flow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:83
msgid ""
"The data flow in Scrapy is controlled by the execution engine, and goes like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:86
msgid ""
"The Engine opens a domain, locates the Spider that handles that domain, and "
"asks the spider for the first URLs to crawl."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:89
msgid ""
"The Engine gets the first URLs to crawl from the Spider and schedules them "
"in the Scheduler, as Requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:92
msgid "The Engine asks the Scheduler for the next URLs to crawl."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:94
msgid ""
"The Scheduler returns the next URLs to crawl to the Engine and the Engine "
"sends them to the Downloader, passing through the Downloader Middleware "
"(request direction)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:98
msgid ""
"Once the page finishes downloading the Downloader generates a Response (with "
"that page) and sends it to the Engine, passing through the Downloader "
"Middleware (response direction)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:102
msgid ""
"The Engine receives the Response from the Downloader and sends it to the "
"Spider for processing, passing through the Spider Middleware (input "
"direction)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:105
msgid ""
"The Spider processes the Response and returns scraped Items and new Requests "
"(to follow) to the Engine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:108
msgid ""
"The Engine sends scraped Items (returned by the Spider) to the Item Pipeline "
"and Requests (returned by spider) to the Scheduler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:111
msgid ""
"The process repeats (from step 2) until there are no more requests from the "
"Scheduler, and the Engine closes the domain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:115
msgid "Event-driven networking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/architecture.rst:117
msgid ""
"Scrapy is written with `Twisted`_, a popular event-driven networking "
"framework for Python. Thus, it's implemented using a non-blocking (aka "
"asynchronous) code for concurrency."
msgstr ""

